No reality to speak of, nobody here but us puppets, contradictory beings, mutants who embody the contorted logic of a paradox.

Correct, the structure of the brain itself is the important part, not the body shape.
As I pointed out before, body size compared to brian size is the only factor that the body really contributes to the equation of intelligence. For example, if you're looking at a whale's huge brain, a lot of that brain mass is needed just to control the massive body, and so not all of that extra brain is contributing to intellect.

There are a lot of exceptions to that trend though, like invertebrates, or extremely small animals.
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brain-to-body_mass_ratio

A more relevant consideration would be something like: do you have to add more regions to the brain or change the function of the nervous system for this anthropomorphization (which you might have to do if you were humanizing insects, for example).
